6px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Take economics. The economics that I studied in co=
llege, except for one frisky Behavioral Economics course, assumes that &#82=
20;economic man&#8221; is perfectly rational and seeks to fit the economy i=
nto a series of differential equations and supply-demand curves on top of t=
hose assumptions. It seeks equilibrium. It&#8217;s mathematically elegant, =
all fits together, and&#8230; is pretty much entirely disconnected from rea=
lity.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The real economy, like most complex systems, doesn&=
#8217;t reach equilibrium. It evolves, based on the actions, rational and i=
rrational, of its billions of individual participants.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D=
"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">Gr=
okking the status quo&#8217;s shortcomings, and armed with the heretical id=
ea of increasing returns &#8211; a concept familiar to all of us in tech to=
day but much less accepted in the early 1980s &#8211; Stanford economist Br=
ian Arthur set out to create a new economic framework at Santa Fe.&nbsp;</p=
><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 =
0 1em 0;">The stakes were more than academic. The world was coming out of a=
 painful period of stagflation in the 1970s that called into question the K=
eynesians&#8217; ability to stabilize the economy. A more realistic economi=
c framework would help policymakers and financiers design interventions tha=
t would stimulate growth and employment, stabilize the market, and better a=
chieve the goals of their fiscal and monetary programs.&nbsp;</p><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;"=
>So instead of differential equations based on assumptions, Arthur proposed=
 agent-based simulations:</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #6=
7bdfc; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>I had this notion tha=
t you could have within your office in the university <strong>a little peas=
ant economy developing under a bubble of glass</strong>. Of course, it woul=
d really be in a computer. But it would have to be all these little agents,=
 preprogrammed to get smart and interact with each other.&nbsp;</em></p><p =
style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1e=
m 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em>Then in this dreamlike idea, you&#8217;d go in =
one morning and say, &#8216;Hey, look at these guys! Two or three weeks ago=
 all they were doing was bartering and now they&#8217;ve got joint stock co=
mpanies.&#8217; Then the next day you&#8217;d come in and say, &#8216;Oh &#=
8211; they&#8217;ve discovered central banking.&#8217; Then a few days late=
r you&#8217;d have all your colleagues clustered around you and you&#8217;r=
e peering in: &#8216;Wow! They&#8217;ve got labor unions! What&#8217;ll the=
y think of next?&#8217; Or half of them have gone Communist.&nbsp;</em></p>=
